Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud Bolton was born in 1221, in Wales as the daughter of Bolton. She had at least 1 daughter with David de Barry. She died in 1254, in Ireland, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1221–1254":"1221–1254","1225–1275":"1225–1275","1249–Female":"1249–Surnud","1190–1270":"1190–1270","1190":"1190","1249":"1249","       1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1221":"1221","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Wales":"Wales","Olethan,Cork,Ireland":"Olethan, County Cork, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1221–1254":"1221–1254","1225–1275":"1225–1275","1249–Female":"1249–Kuollut","1190–1270":"1190–1270","1190":"1190","1249":"1249","       1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1221":"1221","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","Ireland":"Irlanti","Wales":"Wales","Olethan,Cork,Ireland":"Olethan, County Cork, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1221–1254":"1221–1254","1225–1275":"1225–1275","1249–Female":"1249–Décédée","1190–1270":"1190–1270","1190":"1190","1249":"1249","       1249":"1249","1225":"1225","1221":"1221","1254":"1254","1275":"1275","1270":"1270","Ireland":"Irlande","Wales":"